ust as the coronavirus outbreak hits demand.\n\nSaudi Arabia will raise production and offer its crude at deep discounts to win new customers next month, according to two people familiar with the country's oil policy, which risks sending prices tumbling after they already dropped by a third since January to near $45 a barrel.\n\nSaudi Arabia will pump more than 10m barrels a day next month while announcing unprecedented discounts of almost 20 per cent in key markets, in an apparent attempt to punish Russia, while squeezing the US shale industry and other higher cost producers.\n\nProduction could eventually go above 11m b/d, one of the people said, well above the roughly 9m the kingdom had previously been proposing lowering its output to.\n\nSaudi Arabia had last week sought the support of Opec and allies outside the cartel, such as Russia, for a substantial cut in production to stabilise the oil market, which has been reeling as the spread of coronavirus hits the global economy and saps demand for crude.\n\nBut Russia torpedoed the plan, eyeing an opportunity to hit US shale producers, infuriating the kingdom and resulting in the countries removing all restrictions on their output from April.\n\n\"Opec and other countries including Russia couldn't get an agreement. If others will push their production, why is Saudi Arabia not doing the same,\" said a second person familiar with the kingdom's output policy.\n\n\"Now we have the right to sell more to compensate for any loss in prices.\"\n\nThe last price war in 2014 upended the global oil industry, inflicting pain on producers from the North Sea to North Dakota, and forcing them to adapt to the decisive end of the $100-oil era.\n\nHigher output from Saudi Arabia would again hit the US shale sector, the rapid growth of which over the past decade has made the US the world's top producer and forced rivals such as Opec to previously restrict output in a bid to prop up the price.\n\nThe US shale industry has struggled to generate consistent profits, however, and is struggling with tighter access to financing, leaving it vulnerable.\n\nBut the kingdom appears to be targeting Russia in particular.\n\nSaudi Arabia is set to announce that it will sell its crude into north west Europe, a key market for Russian barrels, at discounts to its reference price of more than $8 a barrel compared to March, according to an official price list seen by the Financial Times.\n\nIn the US it is also set to discount its crude by around $7 a barrel in April compared with March. It also made prices cuts to Asia of between $4-6 a barrel.\n\nMonthly price adjustments are normally only a few cents or at most a dollar or two, leaving little doubt over what the kingdom is hoping to achieve.\n\nSaudi Arabia's 12m b/d production capacity has largely been restored after the drone and missile strikes on its key facilities in September.\n\nThe kingdom maintains the most spare production capacity globally, allowing it to raise its output faster than rivals.\n\nThe move will put pressure on Saudi Arabia's allies in the Gulf like the UAE and Kuwait to also cut their prices and potentially increase output to remain competitive.\n\nA price war is likely to prove painful for all sides, but will hit the economies of weaker oil-dependent producers like Nigeria and Angola particularly hard, as they have little scope to increase output and less ability to borrow to plug budget shortfalls.\n\nRussia rejected Saudi Arabia's call to make deeper production cuts on Friday, partly as it wants to try to squeeze the US shale industry and to respond to sanctions Washington has targeted against its energy industry, according to three people present at the meeting between Opec and its allies on Friday.\n\nThe price cuts threaten to further weigh on international oil prices, with Brent already down from $70 a barrel in early January to near $45 a barrel. It fell 9 per cent on Friday alone after the so-called Opec+ deal unravelled.\n\nThere is a chance Saudi Arabia is betting the price war could bring Russia back to the negotiating table to discuss cutting output to try to rescue the price.\n\nBut the atmosphere between the Saudi and Russian camps has soured. Russian president Vladimir Putin rejected requests from Saudi Arabia's King Salman for a rapid response to the effect of coronavirus on the oil market in February.\n\nMoscow's refusal to co-operate, combined with a lack of compliance with oil cuts in recent months, had left the kingdom questioning the reliability of its partner, two people familiar with the matter said.\n\nTraders and analysts have warned an all-out price war could see oil prices fall to $30 a barrel or lower.\n\nRystad Energy analyst Bjornar Tonhaugen said the oil market was now facing \"both an unprecedented demand and supply shock simultaneously\".\n\nA price war would also bring back memories of the last time Saudi Arabia opened the taps in 2014.\n\nThat move, which only succeeded in temporarily slowing down the shale industry, ultimately proved too costly and forced the creation of the oil-based alliance with Russia in 2016 to stop the price rout.\n\nThe difference back then was oil demand was growing, while in 2020 the world's largest traders already believe consumption could fall as the coronavirus crimps air travel and the wider economy.\n\nThe size of the Saudi price cuts are also more aggressive than in 2014, suggesting Saudi Arabia's energy minister Prince Abdulaziz bin Salman has been given the green light to directly target the kingdom's biggest rivals.", "source": {"uri": "ft.com", "dataType": "news", "title": "Financial Times"}, "authors": [], "concepts": [{"uri": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shale", "type": "wiki", "score": 5, "label": {"eng": "Shale"}}, {"uri": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barrel_(unit)", "type": "wiki", "score": 5, "label": {"eng": "Barrel (unit)"}}, {"uri": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petroleum", "type": "wiki", "score": 5, "label": {"en