9c2307bcd4", "title": "Changing mood as Europe shows a harder face on migration", "body": "Confronted by the prospect of thousands of refugees arriving on its southern borders, Europe is showing a far harder face to the outsiders than it did half a decade ago.\n\nThe change in mood -- epitomised by European Commission president Ursula von der Leyen's praise for Greece as a \"shield\" against asylum seekers and migrants -- reflects how far politics within Europe have changed since the crisis of 2015, when a record 1.3m migrants applied for asylum in the bloc, many of them seeking to escape the violence in Syria, Iraq and Afghanistan.\n\nThe influx was consequential for a number of member states, but nowhere more so than Germany, where Chancellor Angela Merkel sparked intense controversy with her decision to welcome hundreds of thousands of Syrian refugees to the country.\n\nAs European foreign ministers prepare for an emergency meeting in Zagreb on Friday, the political mood on the continent has become markedly colder and more defensive -- driven in part by the resurgence of nativist far-right parties across the continent since the 2015 crisis.\n\nThis week a triumphant Viktor Orban, the hardline Hungarian premier, claimed victory in the EU's debate on migration, saying the days when his country was \"subjected to insults for protecting our borders\" were now over.\n\nThe European Commission, which in 2015 tried to impose a system of mandatory relocation of asylum seekers across Europe, is now criticised for failing to condemn the actions of Greek authorities, who have been seen using rubber bullets and tear gas against refugees and migrants at the border.\n\nWhen asked if the use of rubber bullets contravened international human rights, Margaritis Schinas, the Greek commissioner in charge of promoting the European way of life, said it was not for \"the Commission to offer an operational opinion or judgment on a situation which is exceptional\". Eric Mamer, spokesman for the commission, on Thursday said it was not possible to \"give a yes or no answer\" to the question.\n\nTo some politicians the harsher approach is dismaying -- a sign that an insecure Europe is turning inward while failing to create common integration and asylum policies that would create a more equitable internal system and allow legal routes for migration.\n\nTanja Fajon, a centre-left Slovene MEP, said: \"We are building fences and border walls instead of common European solutions.\"\n\nSome diplomats argue Europe's new anti-migrant consensus is far from surprising given the scale of the influx in 2015. EU leaders are also anxious to display a united and determined front in the face of what they see as blackmail by Turkey's president, Recep Tayyip Erdogan. The EU has failed to create a durable process for redistributing refugees who arrive on the continent, prompting it to concentrate on forging alliances to keep potential migrants in other countries -- most prominently Turkey -- while attempting to fortify its external borders.\n\nThis week Ms Von der Leyen said the EU would be making \u20ac700m available for the refugee crisis on the Greek/Turkish border, and despatching a force from its border management agency Frontex to include seven vessels, two helicopters, one plane, three thermal-vision vehicles and 100 extra border guards.\n\n\"If the EU had a solidarity mechanism in place it would come to the table in a different position,\" said Hanne Beirens, director of the Migration Policy Institute Europe think-tank. \"We look very weak for the moment when we come to the negotiating table with Turkey.\"\n\nAcross Europe, politicians of the centre-left and centre-right calculate that they can no longer be seen to be soft on migration and border control. In response to the presence of avowedly far-right parties like the Alternative for Germany or Austria's Freedom Party, Europe's parties of government -- including the centre-left in Denmark or Emmanuel Macron's La R\u00e9publique en Marche -- have turned hawkish on migration.\n\n\"Since 2015, the de facto migration policy of the EU is unanimously one of Fortress Europe,\" says Philippe Lamberts, co-leader of the EU's green party.\n\nMr Lamberts said that unlike in 2015 -- when the volume of newcomers was upwards of 1m -- numbers in Greece are still in the tens of thousands.\n\nOn Sunday the Hungarian government moved to close camps or \"transit zones\" for asylum seekers along its southern border with Serbia, saying in a statement that \"coronavirus and illegal migration go hand in hand\".\n\nThe move to stop accepting asylum applications -- which has also been imposed in Greece -- appears to be in breach of international law, according to the UN Refugee Agency.\n\nHungary's justice minister Judit Varga defended the move to block access to the transit zones. \"There is a situation of the virus, this is the legal reasoning,\" Ms Varga told the Financial Times, confirming that the decision was made for an indefinite period of time. \"This is a temporary tool, which can be used by any kind of state based on disclosure of the public health crisis,\" she said, referencing the coronavirus outbreak.\n\nBut it is no longer just Mr Orban who stands at the vanguard of Europe's border policy. The EU's top brass -- including Ms von der Leyen and Charles Michel, council president -- are also under fire for lavishing praise on Greek authorities this week amid violence on Greece's border with Turkey.\n\nLuxembourg's foreign minister Jean Asselborn on Wednesday urged the EU not to turn its back on its fundamental values. \"It is inhuman and un-European to close your eyes. Every member country of the EU has its duties. Europe must be able to help the Greeks concretely, in accordance with and with respect to the Geneva Convention,\" he said.", "source": {"uri": "ft.com", "dataType": "news", "title": "Financial Times"}, "authors": [], "concepts": [{"uri": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asyl