 a project-ending nightmare, here the developers decided instead to capitalise on the discoveries -- ripping up the original plans and creating a dramatic modern building that hovers above the mosaics, columns and ancient walls.\n\nDesigned by the Turkish architect Emre Arolat, also responsible for the sublime Sancaklar Mosque in Istanbul (a building that classicist Mary Beard described as \"one of the most striking religious creations of modern times\"), the hotel's five floors are suspended from steel girders carried by 66 columns. Arolat has called the hotel the project of his life. The lowest floor houses the museum, above that is the hotel's reception, then bars and restaurants connected by walkways. A honeycomb of stacked bedroom pods hangs in the void of the atrium, open to the elements on its flanks.\n\nOn top, Arolat has placed a presidential suite, a fitness and health spa with Turkish bath -- where I enjoyed that hammam -- a ballroom, more restaurants, conference facilities, inside and outside pools and wide roof terraces that look over the bulk of Mount Silpius.\n\nAll this is waiting for the world to marvel at. But will it come?\n\nAfter more than a decade of work, the timing for the launch of the hotel could scarcely be worse. Antakya, capital of Turkey's Hatay region, is wedged between the Mediterranean and north-western Syria. Presently, the British Foreign Office advises against all but essential travel to Hatay province; the US State Department suggests potential visitors should \"reconsider\". The official opening was in January, and international journalists were invited to see it last month, just as tensions between Turkey and Syria escalated and days before 34 Turkish troops were killed in Idlib. And meanwhile the escalating coronavirus crisis has put even more people off leaving home.\n\nThe Syrian border is just 20km away from Antakya, Idlib only another 33km -- now is clearly not the time to go -- even though as dusk falls on the terrace outside my room, much older disasters seem closer at hand than the neighbouring civil war. The mosaics and slabs beneath carry the mark of fire and invasion and the many earthquakes that obliterated the site for 1,500 years until work started in 2009.\n\nAt that point, tourism was on the rise and trade with Syria was strong. The Asfuroglu group, a construction company, began work on a hotel on a block of land it had owned since the 1990s and which had been used for processing and selling cement. The location in the old city, just below St Peter's cave church, where the apostle and St Paul are believed to have worshipped, and close to the world-class archaeology museum, appeared perfectly positioned for an expected boom in visitors intrigued by the city's past and its cuisine, a sumptuous meld of Arab and Turkish elements (which in 2017 won Antakya recognition as a Unesco \"City of Gastronomy\").\n\nAs one of the conditions of planning permission, a team from the museum of archaeology sank 29 exploratory shafts. Sabiha Asfuroglu Abbasoglu, chief executive of the Asfuroglu group's hotel division, was on site when the drilling began. \"We had no clue what was down there,\" she says, when we meet on the caf\u00e9 terrace overlooking the forum and sip fierce Antakya coffee (\"It's like Turkish coffee but even stronger!\"). \"But every single one of these exploratory shafts revealed something. We knew that the original plan was over.\"\n\nConstruction was stopped and the biggest systematic archaeological dig in the region since the 1930s began. One of the first discoveries was a marble statue of Eros, dated to 200AD, now one of the highlights of the hotel museum. And then there is the world's largest single floor mosaic, 1,050 sq metres of geometric pattern rippled into a wave effect by subsidence. In 2012 they discovered the Pegasus mosaic, a mythological scene of staggering subtlety, in which 160 different shades of stone have been identified.\n\nIn all, some 30,000 objects from 13 different civilisations were discovered. Many of those finds are in the Antakya Archaeology Museum -- itself a pretty astonishing institution. The hotel's framework used 20,000 tons of steel, three times more, they like to tell you, than went into the Eiffel Tower.\n\nUnderstandably, Abbasoglu, although only 36, has the manner of someone who has been through a lifetime's labour. \"It was very difficult,\" she says with some understatement. \"Every day there was a new problem to deal with.\"\n\nThe original budget was $40m and as the costs rose the group sold assets to foot the bill. \"Financially it was very hard and we had to sell much of our land around Hatay and a hospital we owned.\" When I ask the final cost Abbasoglu flips currencies, as if it might soften the blow. \"More than \u20ac120m.\"\n\nWas it worth it? \"This is not just a hotel and museum,\" she says. \"It is my life, it is my family's life.\" Her pride is palpable but there is also exasperation. Antakya is unique in the Levant for the way its faith communities, Sunni, Alawite, Orthodox, Catholic and Jewish, coexist. For the city's business community, the UK and US travel advice implies turmoil where they see none. \"It has been a difficult time for the region and for tourism, but we've not been directly affected in Antakya and life goes on as normal for us here,\" says Abbasoglu. \"We look forward with hope.\"\n\nSeeing the treasure that the project has uncovered might not count as \"essential travel\" but it is certainly hard to forget. Before I leave, there is one thing I must see again. Not the Pegasus mosaic or the statue of Eros, but that stretch of apparently ageless road. I find a Turkish woman already there and she tells me it is her favourite place as well. \"If you're quiet,\" she says, \"you can hear their sandals on the stone.\" So we stand silently together, lost, just for a moment, in antiquity.\n\nTravel and travel planning are being disrupted by the worldwide spread of the 