ease or that they become sick,\" the World Organisation for Animal Health said in a statement this week.\n\nIan Mackay, University of Queensland virologist, told the Financial Times last week domestic animals were unlikely to become a significant route for human infection, while Hong Kong University microbiologist Ho Pak-leung said the chance of dog-to-human transmission was \"very small\".\n\n\"Even if the cats and dogs cough droplets, they would not go too far,\" Dr Ho said.\n\nIt was more likely that humans would infect their dogs than the other way around, the experts said.\n\n\"If anything, this highlights that we humans still need to be more careful to avoid infecting other loved ones in our household, furry or not,\" Dr Mackay said.\n\nThomas Sit, assistant director of Agriculture, Fisheries and Conservation in Hong Kong, said that during the Sars outbreak, the infected cats carried the virus longer than the dog that was infected. However, there was no evidence that cats could transmit it to other cats.\n\n\"To date, there is no evidence that companion animals can spread the disease. Therefore, there is no justification in taking measures against companion animals which may compromise their welfare,\" the World Organisation for Animal Health said.\n\nHowever, experts are also urging people to take precautions. In a Facebook post cuddling his pet Schnauzer, Hong Kong University's Dr Ho said: \"Dogs should remain a safe social distance [from] one another.\"\n\nHe also urged people to clean up after their dogs in the street.\n\nThe Pomeranian has shown no symptoms of the illness.\n\nHong Kong authorities are \"strongly advising\" the quarantine of \"mammalian pet animals including dogs and cats\" belonging to people who have been infected with coronavirus.\n\nBy Thursday afternoon, just one cat and one dog aside from the Pomeranian were under quarantine, and both had tested negative.\n\nThe World Organisation for Animal Health said keeping animals that test posi